Clinton campaign bigs Robby Mook, Mark Elias on witness list for trial from Durham probe

Several high-profile Democratic political operatives and officials are set to take the witness stand next week in the trial of former Clinton campaign attorney Michael Sussmann.

Robby Mook, who managed Hillary Clinton‚Äôs 2016 campaign, Clinton campaign attorney Marc Elias and FBI counterintelligence leader Bill Priestap and former top FBI lawyer James Baker are among those called as government witnesses.

The prosecution spearheaded by special counsel John Durham‚Äòs probe of the FBI‚Äòs Trump-Russia collusion investigation also will put on the stand:

- Laura Seago, a top tech official at research firm Fusion GPS;

- Deborah Fine, a Clinton campaign lawyer; and

- A CIA official identified only as ‚ÄúKevin B.‚Äù¬†

Defense attorneys unveiled their own high-powered witness list. It includes Justice Department Inspector General Michael Horowitz, former acting Assistant Attorney General Mary McCord and Pulitzer Prize-winning New York Times reporter Eric Lichtblau.

Mr. Durham has charged Mr. Sussmann ‚Äî whose firm Perkins Coie represented the Clinton campaign and the Democratic National Committee ‚Äî with lying to the FBI in September 2016 when he provided Mr. Baker with evidence of a purported link between Mr. Trump and Russia‚Äòs Alfa Bank.

Mr. Durham alleges that the Democratic attorney concealed that he was acting on behalf of the Clinton campaign.

Prosecutors say Mr. Sussmann later billed the Clinton campaign for the time he spent peddling the now-debunked link between Mr. Trump and the Russian bank. His trial starts next week.

FIVE FUNNY FUNDS by Cheryl Tillman
30 APR 2022

In the last post, I mentioned 4 other funds besides the Center for Tech and Civic Life (CTCL), and the Run For Something program. Here is my research on each one from their websites and other sources. Notice how these funds and non-profits overlap quite a bit with non-profits that are funded by other non-profits or corporations, making the whole scheme quite complex.

The 5 Funny Funds are:

1. Run for Something (RFS); www.runforsomething.net; is a political action committee and its website states that its mission is to get progressives under the age of 40 to run for down ballot races. It was launched by Amanda Litman, a staffer on Hillary‚Äôs campaign. There is also a Run for Something Action Fund non-profit for donations.

This $80M three-year program helps and endorses candidates that support illegal immigration, abortion, gun control, government-run healthcare, etc. This program is suspiciously similar to the CTCL $80M, don't you think? (Source: Politico)

2. Center For Civic Design, Inc. (CCD), www.civicdesign.org is a non-profit in Maryland; Their information starts out great‚Äîwe all want improved and easy to read voting instructions‚Äîbut then they give it that Left Twist and the good stuff is squeezed out. Their best practices to ‚Äúimprove the voter experience‚Äù include:
¬∑ Tooklit for scaling up voting by mail. [the largest area for frawed.]
¬∑ Vote-at-home envelopes, materials, and workbook
¬∑ Designs for Ranked Choice Voting
¬∑ An ‚ÄúAnywhere ballot‚Äù

One of their partners is CTCL, which has a board member on CCD. ‚ÄúWe actively seek out and listen to those who are excluded from voting‚Äù.

They have free resources, one to prevent misinformation for ‚Äúinfluence operations‚Äù and tell us how and what to respond. They tell you how to set up a website or other site to make it look official. They provide contacts on how to report ‚Äúvoter interference‚Äù. They also provide how to work with fact-checking organizations.

3. The Elections Group (EG), www.electionsgroup.com; is a for-profit group that works quickly to provide guidance, resources and direct management support.‚Äù They also have free downloads, to help decide which type of ballot drop boxes you need, how many you need, how to promote them and hire and train staff. And they work with CTCL for a Ballot Drop-Off Location Criteria Planner to help with the location!

Chief Operating Officer Chris Piper worked for radical VA Governor Ralph ‚ÄúDefender-of-Infanticide‚Äù Northam, and served on the board of Bad Boy ERIC (see my previous research). Two other leaders worked with the U.S. Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA). Remember them? CISA said that the 2o2o election was ‚Äúthe most secure election in history‚Äù and President Tr‚Äôumph later fired its director.

4. U.S. Digital Response (USDR), www.usdigitalresponse.org; this non-profit says they‚Äôre ‚Äúfast, free, and non-partisan‚Äù. USDR provides free rapid response assistance to election offices, small or large, in support of critical public needs. They hire un-paid volunteers.

Is USDR really non-partisan? Two of its partners are leftist groups, the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation and the Rockefeller Foundation. The CCD (above) Chair of the Board is an advisor. USDR received a major grant from‚Äîyou guessed it‚ÄîCTCL, they declined to disclose the value, but it was ‚Äúmulti-million dollar‚Äù. (Source: StateScoop 26 Apr 2022). I would say they aren‚Äôt non-partisan.

USDR advocates for new voting equipment because ‚Äúwe cannot afford government‚Äôs outdated processes any longer.‚Äù Their newest program uses open-source technologies [made who-knows-where] to build poll location search tools, websites, and apps to manage us poll workers.

5. Center for Secure and Modern Elections (CSME); www.modernelections.org advocates for automatic electronic registration systems to ‚Äúprotect the security of our elections‚Äù. They say ‚Äúmodernizing our outdated, paper-based voter registration system is just common sense.‚Äù I could not find any connection to the Bad Boy ERIC system.
